oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Zinc-selective Inhibition of the Promiscuous Bacterial Amide-Hydrolase DapE: Implications of Metal Heterogeneity in Evolution and Antibiotic Drug-Design
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Uda, Narasimha Rao; Upert, Gr√©gory; Angelici, Gaetano; Nicolet, Stefan; Schmidt, Tobias; Schwede, Torsten; Creus, Marc
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The development of resistance to virtually all current antibiotics makes the discovery of new antimicrobial compounds to novel protein targets an urgent challenge. The dapE-encoded N-succinyl-L,L-diaminopimelic acid desuccinylase (DapE) is an essential metallo-enzyme for growth and proliferation in many bacteria, acting in the desuccinylation of N-succinyl-L,L-diaminopimelic acid (SDAP) in a late stage of the anabolic pathway towards both lysine and a crucial building block of the peptidoglycan cell wall. L-captopril, which has been shown to exhibit very promising inhibitory activity in vitro against DapE and has attractive drug-like properties, nevertheless does not target DapE in bacteria effectively. Here we show that L-captopril targets only the Zn2+-metallo-isoform of the enzyme, whereas the Mn2+-enzyme, which is also a physiologically-relevant isoform in bacteria, is not inhibited. Our finding provides a rational for the failure of this promising lead-compound to exhibit any significant antibiotic activity in bacteria and underlines the importance of addressing metallo-isoform heterogeneity in future drug design. Moreover, to our knowledge, this is the first example of metallo-isoform heterogeneity in vivo that provides an evolutionary advantage to bacteria upon drug-challenge.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Evolution of substrate specificity in bacterial AA10 lytic polysaccharide monooxygenases
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Book, Adam J.; Yennamalli, Ragothaman M.; Takasuka, Taichi E.; Currie, Cameron R.; Phillips Jr., George N.; Fox, Brian G.
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Understanding the diversity of lignocellulose degrading enzymes in nature will provide insights for the improvement of cellulolytic enzyme cocktails used in the biofuels industry. Two families of enzymes, fungal AA9 and bacterial AA10, have recently been characterized as crystalline cellulose or chitin cleaving lytic polysaccharide monooxygenases (LPMOs). Here we analyze the sequences, structures, and evolution of LPMOs to understand the factors that may influence substrate specificity both within and between these enzyme families. The absence of significant sequence similarity between AA9 and AA10 families suggests that these enzyme families either shared a very ancient ancestral protein or that they converged onto a similar biochemical function from unrelated sequences. Combined analysis of amino acid sites under Darwinian selection and structural homology modeling identified a subclade of AA10 with diversifying selection at surfaces potentially used for cellulose-binding and protein-protein interactions. Together, these data indicate that AA10 LPMOs are under selection to change, which may optimize cellulolytic activity. This work provides a framework for identifying and classifying additional cellulolytic or chitonolytic LPMOs for use in biochemical research and the biofuels industry.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: ATP8A2 MD-refined membrane domain E2 and E2P homology models
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Vestergaard, Anna L.; Coleman, Jonathan A.; Lemmin, Thomas; Mikkelsen, Stine A.; Molday, Laurie L.; Vilsen, Bente; Molday, Robert S.; Dal Peraro, Matteo; Andersen, Jens Peter
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: P4-ATPases (flippases) translocate specific phospholipids such as phosphatidylserine from the exoplasmic leaflet of the cell membrane to the cytosolic leaflet, upholding an essential membrane asymmetry. The mechanism of flipping this ‚Äúgiant substrate‚Äù has remained an enigma. We have investigated the importance of amino acid residues in the membrane domain of bovine P4-ATPase ATP8A2 by mutagenesis, and we have identified certain residues of importance for the transport mechanism (1,2). Our functional studies are backed up by structural homology modeling of E2P and E2 conformations, based on a large multiple alignment of P-type ATPases and the SERCA crystal structures 3B9B and 3AR4, respectively (1,*). The membrane domains of the models were refined by 100 ns molecular dynamics simulations, of which the latter 20 ns were stable. Frames after 87.4 and 100 ns are deposited here. The MD simulations suggest that a cluster of conserved hydrophobic residues function as a hydrophobic gate that separates the entry and exit sites of the lipid and directs sequential formation and annihilation of water-filled cavities. This may enable transport of the hydrophilic phospholipid head group in a groove outlined by the transmembrane segments M1, M2, M4, and M6, with the hydrocarbon chains following passively, still in the membrane lipid phase. 1. Vestergaard, A.L. et al., Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A, 2014. 111(14): p. E1334-43. 2. Coleman, J.A. et al., Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A, 2012. 109(5): p. 1449-54. * We thank Marco Biasini and Torsten Schwede (Biozentrum, University of Basel and Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics) for expert guidance on multiple alignment and homology modeling.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Signatures of APOBEC3's specificity and vulnerability to HIV-1 Vif
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Shandilya, Shivender M. D.; Bohn, Markus-Frederik; Schiffer, Celia A.
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: APOBEC3s (A3) are Zn2+ dependent cytidine deaminases with diverse biological functions and implications in cancer and immune response. Four of the seven human A3s restrict HIV by rendering the reverse-transcribed viral genomic DNA ‚Äôhypermutated‚Äô. HIV Virion Infectivity Factor (Vif) counters this restriction by targeting A3s to proteasomal degradation. However, there is no apparent correlation between catalytic activity, Vif binding, and sequence similarity between various A3 domains. In this study, a comparative analysis reveals structural features required for Vif binding, polynucleotide binding, and deam- inase activity in A3 proteins. All Vif-binding A3s share a contiguous negatively charged surface region including residues previously implicated in binding the highly-positively charged Vif. Additionally, catalytically active A3s have a positively charged groove near the Zn2+ coordinating active site, which may accommodate the polynucleotide substrate. Our findings suggest surface electrostatics, along with shape complementarity, are critical determinants of substrate and Vif binding activities across APOBEC3 proteins, with significant implications for anti-retroviral and anti-cancer therapies.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: AtTRB1-3 interacts with AtPOT1b in order to recruit telomerase towards telomere
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Jaiswal, Amit
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description:
Telomere repeat binding factor (TRB) are essential proteins which binds to telomeric DNA in complex with Protection of telomere 1 (POT1) protein and recruits telomerase for maintaining the telomeric ends [1, 2]. In Arabidopsis thaliana, there are three types of TRB namely TRB1, TRB2 and TRB3 and three types of POT1 homologs namely POT1a, POT1b and POT1c respectively, where POT1a works in complex with telomerase for synthesis of telomeres while POT1b and POT1c are helps in chromosome end protection [3]. Physical association between AtTRB1-3 and AtPOT1 has also been proved previously with unknown reasons [4, 5]. However, recently it has been shown that AtTRB's interaction with AtPOT1b brings structural changes in the later to hold single strand DNA (ssDNA) more efficiently and makes ssDNA highly stable in nature [6]. This efficient binding would facilitate the telomerase to come and sit on ssDNA in order to synthesize telomeric DNA more efficiently. Moreover, structural information about the above mentioned proteins helped a lot in designing peptides in order to inhibit telomerase recruitment towards telomeres [7].

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Modeling the protein encoded by the Populus deltoides Kunitz Trypsin Inhibitor 3 gene, up-regulated under copper stress
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Reyes, Luz; Vergara, Ariela; Guerra, Fernando
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Poplar trees (Populus spp) have been proposed as candidate species for phytoremediation of heavy metals. Copper is an essential micronutrient for plants and a common pollutant in some countries. In previous studies, we identified a suite of genes differentially expressed in poplars subjected to copper excess. That included some genes encoding members of the Kunitz trypsin inhibitor (KTI) protein family, traditionally associated with the cell defense against herbivores and pathogen attack. However, the relationship of KTIs and heavy metal stress is scarcely known. In order to determine the role of KTIs in the mechanisms of copper tolerance, we focused this study on the structural and functional characterization of the Populus deltoides KTI3 gene (PdKTI3). PdKTI3 was isolated and sequenced, and its protein structure was modeled. The predicted structure showed two putative copper binding domains, suggesting the ability of the protein for chelating this metal. Additionally, expression analyses showed a significant up regulation of PdKTI3, in both roots and leaves, when hydroponically grown poplars were treated with copper excess. Furthermore, the expression of PdKTI3 in copper-sensitive mutant yeasts reversed the phenotype when they were exposed to copper and cadmium stress. Results suggest a novel role for the evaluated KTI. PdKTI3 would be a chelating protein, participating as part of the defense mechanisms induced by copper stress.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: PgLB
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Haas, Juergen; Schwede, Torsten
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Conjugate vaccines belong to the most efficient preventive measures against life-threatening bacterial infections. Functional expression of N-oligosaccharyltransferase PglB of Campylobacter jejuni in Escherichia coli enables a simplified production of glycoconjugate vaccines in prokaryotic cells. Polysaccharide antigens of pathogenic bacteria can be covalently coupled to immunogenic acceptor proteins bearing engineered glycosylation sites. Transfer efficiency of PglBCj depends on an N-acetyl functionality at the carbon 2 of the reducing end monosaccharide, and polysaccharides lacking this C2 N-acetyl groups are transferred inefficiently. In this study, we increased glycosylation rates for Salmonella enterica sv. Typhimurium LT2 O antigen, which lacks N-acetyl sugars and Staphylococcus aureus CP5 polysaccharides by structure-guided engineering of PglB. A three-dimensional homology model of membrane-associated PglBCj with the docked natural C. jejuni N-glycan attached to the acceptor peptide was used to identify potential sugar-interacting residues as targets for mutagenesis. A library with randomised active site residue N311 reproducibly yielded the beneficial mutation N311V which lead to 5 to 11-fold increased in vivo glycosylation rates as determined by glycoprotein-specific ELISA. Further rounds of in vitro evolution lead to a triple mutant S80R-Q287-N311V which increased the yield of metal affinity purified S. enterica LT2 glycoconjugates by a factor of 16. Thus, the variant enzyme was capable of linking polysaccharides with a galactose at the reducing end to acceptor proteins. All beneficial mutations resided in periplasmic, elongated loops of the transmembrane part of PglB. We show for the first time that directed evolution of PglB can lead to increased glycosylation efficiency.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Truncated mutant of RPA-1 from Leishmania amazonensis (LaRPA-1) without OB-fold domains 1 and 2 (LaRPA-1DeltaOBF1,2)
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Fernandes, Carlos Alexandre Henrique; Pavani, Raphael Silva; Cano, Maria Isabel Nogueira; Fontes, Marcos Roberto de Mattos
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Replication protein A-1 (RPA-1) is a single-stranded DNA-binding protein involved in DNA metabolism. RPA-1 from Leishmania amazonensis (LaRPA-1) interacts with telomeric DNA. LaRPA-1 interacts with telomeric ssDNA only via its N-terminal OB-fold domain (OBF1), whereas RPA from higher eukaryotes show different binding modes to ssDNA. LaRPA-1DeltaOBF1,2 model shows that the residues involved in DNA binding are buried in the inner of the protein, occluding DNA access to the LaRPA-1 OBF3 binding site. However, the Cys4-type zinc ribbon motif is conserved and LaRPA-1 could retain the ability to bind zinc.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Tobacco calmodulin-like protein rgs-CaM in silico model with calcium ions loaded in calcium four putative calcium binding loops
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Fernandes, Carlos Alexandre Henrique; Matioli, F√°bio Fillipi; Fontes, Marcos Roberto de Mattos; Maia, Ivan de Godoy
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Tobbaco calmodulin-like protein rgs-CaM displays two EF-hands motifs that contains two putative calcium binding loops each. However, ITC studies showed that rgs-CaM displays only three calcium binding sites. Here, in silico model of rgs-CaM with calcium ions loaded in their four putative calcium binding loops shows that the calcium ion modeled in loop C escaped from the loop along the MD simulations highlighting that loop C is unable to coordinate calcium. In fact, aminoacids sequence comparison shows that loop C does not conserved any residue involved in calcium coordination.

oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Tobbaco calmodulin-like protein rgs-CaM displays three functional calcium binding sites that dissociations constants were not in the range of calcium sensors. Here, we show the in silico model of rgs-CaM with calcium ion modeled on calcium binding loop B. Calcium ions loaded on loops A and/or D causes an expansion of the rgs-CaM tertiary structure. However, loading calcium only on loop B causes a partial compression of tertiary structure, with a radius of gyration value (2.0 nm) intermediate between apo-rgs-CaM (1.7 nm) and rgs-CaM bounded to calcium ions on loops A and/or D (~2.3 nm)

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Tobacco calmodulin-like protein rgs-CaM in silico model with calcium ions loaded in calcium binding loops A, B and D (rgs-CaM+Ca-A-B-D)
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Fernandes, Carlos Alexandre Henrique; Matioli, F√°bio Fillipi; Fontes, Marcos Roberto de Mattos; Maia, Ivan de Godoy
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Tobbaco calmodulin-like protein rgs-CaM displays two EF-hands motifs that contains two putative calcium binding loops each. However, ITC studies showed that rgs-CaM displays only three calcium binding sites, labeled calcium binding loops A, B and D since that putative loop C is not functional. Here, in silico model of rgs-CaM with calcium ions loaded in its three functional calcium binding loops (rgs-CaM+Ca-A-B-D) shows that calcium binding leads to a expansion of the tertiary structure (radius of gyration of 2.3 nm in contrast of 1.7 nm from apo-rgs-Cam) and a reorientation of EF-hands to a more exposition to the solvent. Along the MD simulations, a region near the middle of central helix (E120-E125) presented a great mobility confering to this central helix a flexibility that contributes to the reorientation of the EF-hands. Amino acids sequence comparison with classical calmodulin shows that E120-E125 region from rgs-CaM is analogous to K77-S81 region from classical calmodulins that also has a high degree of mobility as previously showed by NMR assays. Finally, this expansion of tertiary structure in presence of calcium leads to a exposition of a large negatively charged area that may be responsible for the rgs-CaM interaction with dsRNA-binding domains from viral proteins involved in RNA silecing supression.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: SecDF-concatenated-Pao1
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Navare, Arti; Chanvez, Juan D; Zheng, Chunxiang; Weisbrod, Chad R; Eng, Jimmy K; Siehnel, Richard; Singh, Pradeep K
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: we applied in vivo chemical cross-linking mass spectrometry, to reveal the first large-scale protein interaction network in the Pseudomonas aeruginosa, an opportunistic human pathogen, by covalently linking interacting protein partners, thereby fixing protein complexes in vivo. A total of 626 cross-linked peptide pairs, including previously unknown interactions of many membrane proteins are reported. These pairs not only define the existence of these interactions in cells, but also provide linkage constraints for complex structure predictions. A transmembrane complex between protein SecD and SecF was identified with an unambiguous cross-linked peptide pair. SecD-SecF protein complex is a part of a highly conserved sec machinary in the gram negative bacteria that enables export of protein cargo across the inner membrane. Although reports of successful co-crystallization efforts of SecD and SecF have not yet appeared, the crystal structure of a fused form of SecD and SecF from Thermus thermophilius (TsecDF) is published. Due to the sequence similarities shared by SecD and SecF proteins with the fused TsecDF form, the protein sequences of PAO1 sec proteins were concatenated and the fused PAO1 SecD-SecF and structural model prediction was performed with I-TASSER. The cross-linking derived distance constraint was used to select and filter the resulting computational models.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: OprF-dimer-PAO1
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Navare, Arti; Chanvez, Juan D; Zheng, Chunxiang; Weisbrod, Chad R; Eng, Jimmy K; Siehnel, Richard; Singh, Pradeep K; Manoil, Colin; Bruce, James E
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description:
we applied in vivo chemical cross-linking mass spectrometry, to reveal the first large-scale protein interaction network in the Pseudomonas aeruginosa, an opportunistic human pathogen, by covalently linking interacting protein partners, thereby fixing protein complexes in vivo. A total of 626 cross-linked peptide pairs, including previously unknown interactions of many membrane proteins including major lipoprotein OprF are reported. These pairs not only define the existence of these interactions in cells, but also provide linkage constraints for complex structure predictions. All cross-linked peptide pairs identified in this work are presented in our on-line cross-linked peptide database XLink-DB (http://brucelab.gs.washington.edu/xlinkdb/specViewerPA.php).
Several intra-cross-link peptide pairs from the C-terminal region of oprF were identified, of which two peptide pairs were between peptides of identical sequences. The presence of such homodimeric cross-links confirm the existence of a homodimeric complex of P. aeruginosa OprF. The intra-cross-link site information was applied to guide a computational model of OprF c-terminal region (OmpA-like domain). The top scoring monomeric model was then subjected to symmetric docking to build a dimeric model, using the homodimeric distance constraints.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: The structural model of the toxin Ts4 from Tityus serrulatus scorpion venom
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Arantes, Eliane Candiani; Pucca, Manuela Berto; Cerni, Felipe Augusto; Peigneur, Steve; Bordon, Karla Castro Figueiredo; Tytgat, Jan
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The toxin Ts4 (also named TsTX-VI, Tityustoxin-6, Tityustoxin VI, TsTXVI, Toxin VI, Ts VI and TsNTxP), previously described as a ‚Äúnon-toxic‚Äù toxin, was isolated from the scorpion venom of Tityus serrulatus (Ts), responsible for the most severe and the highest number of accidents in Brazil. In this study, the subtype specificity and selectivity of Ts4 was investigated using six mammalian Nav channels (Nav1.2, Nav1.3, Nav1.4, Nav1.5, Nav1.6, and Nav1.8) and two insect Nav channels (DmNav1 and BgNav). The electrophysiological assays showed that Ts4 specifically inhibited the fast inactivation of Nav1.6 channels with no effect on all the others Nav channels tested. Ts4 is the only Ts toxin with a unique specificity, resulting in its low toxicity. Since Ts4 acts on Nav1.6 channels, the most abundantly sodium channel expressed in the adult central nervous system, it can no longer be classified as a ‚Äúnon-toxic peptide‚Äù. Based on the results, we could classify the Ts4 as a classical Œ±-toxin. The Ts4 3D-structural model was built based on the solved X-ray Ts1 3D-structure, the major toxin from Ts venom with which it shares high sequence identity (65.57 %). The Ts4 model revealed a flattened triangular shape constituted by three-stranded antiparallel Œ≤-sheet and one Œ±-helix stabilized by four disulfide bonds. The absence of a Lys in the first amino acid residue of the N-terminal of Ts4 is probably the main responsible for its low toxicity. Other key amino acid residues important to the toxicity of Œ±- and Œ≤-toxins are discussed here.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: DARC - Duffy Antigen / Receptor for Chemokine (model 1)
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: de Brevern, Alexandre G.
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The Duffy antigen/receptor for chemokine (DARC) is an erythrocyte receptor for malaria parasites (Plasmodium vivax and Plasmodium knowlesi) and for chemokines. In contrast to other chemokine receptors, DARC is a promiscuous receptor that binds chemokines of both CC and CXC classes. The four extracellular domains (ECDs) of DARC are essential for its interaction with chemokines, whilst the first (ECD1) is sufficient for the interaction with malaria erythrocyte-binding protein. In this study, we elaborate and analyze structural models of the DARC. The construction of the 3D models is based on a comparative modeling process and on the use of many procedures to predict transmembrane segments and to detect far homologous proteins with known structures. Threading, ab initio, secondary structure and Protein Blocks approaches are used to build a very large number of models. The conformational exploration of the ECDs is performed with simulated annealing. The second and fourth ECDs are strongly constrained. On the contrary, the ECD1 is highly flexible, but seems composed of three consecutive regions: a small beta-sheet, a linker region and a structured loop. The chosen structural models encompass most of the biochemical features and reflect the known experimental data. They may be used to analyze functional interaction properties. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16046070

oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: de Brevern, Alexandre G.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Mycoplasma pneumoniae ribosome
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Graziadei, Andrea; O Reilly, Francis; Xue, Liang; Mahamid, Julia; Rappsilber, Juri
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Structural biology performed inside cells can capture molecular machines in action within their native context. Here we developed an integrative in-cell structural approach using the genome-reduced human pathogen Mycoplasma pneumoniae. We combined whole-cell crosslinking mass spectrometry, cellular cryo-electron tomography, and integrative modeling to determine an in-cell architecture of a transcribing and translating expressome at sub-nanometer resolution. The expressome comprises RNA polymerase (RNAP), the ribosome, and the transcription elongation factors NusG and NusA. We pinpointed NusA at the interface between a NusG-bound elongating RNAP and the ribosome, and propose it can mediate transcription-translation coupling. Translation inhibition dissociated the expressome, whereas transcription inhibition stalled and rearranged it. Thus, the active expressome architecture requires both translation and transcription elongation within the cell.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: COMPUTATIONAL MODEL STRUCTURE OF SARS-CoV-2 NON-STRUCTURAL PROTEIN 6 (nsp6)
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Baruah, Chittaranjan; Devi, Papari; Baruah, Dhirendra Kumar; Mahanta, Saurov
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The structure of 'SARS-CoV-2 NON-STRUCTURAL PROTEIN 6 (nsp6)‚Äù is a part of the project ‚ÄúIn silico Proteome analysis of Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2)‚Äù (Baruah et al., 2020; In communication) based on the sequence analysis and complete coordinate structure prediction of full SARS-CoV-2 proteome based on the NCBI reference sequence NC_045512 (29903 bp ss-RNA) which is identical to GenBank entry MN908947 and MT415321.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Caspase Domain of Separase from C. elegans
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Winter, Anja; Bayliss, Richard; Schmid, Ralf
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Separases are large proteins that mediate sister chromatid disjunction in all eukaryotes. They belong to clan CD of cysteine peptidases and contain a well-conserved C-terminal catalytic protease domain similar to caspases and gingipains. However, unlike other well-characterized groups of clan CD peptidases, there are no high-resolution structures of separases and the details of their regulation and substrate recognition are poorly understood. Here we undertook an in-depth bioinformatical analysis of separases from different species with respect to their similarity in amino acid sequence and protein fold in comparison to caspases, MALT-1 proteins (mucosa-associated lymphoidtissue lymphoma translocation protein 1) and gingipain-R. A comparative model of the single C-terminal caspase-like domain in separase from C. elegans suggests similar binding modes of substrate peptides between these protein subfamilies, and enables differences in substrate specificity of separase proteins to be rationalised. We also modelled a newly identified putative death domain, located N-terminal to the caspase-like domain. The surface features of this domain identifies potential sites of protein-protein interactions. Notably, we identified a novel conserved region with the consensus sequence WWxxRxxLD, predicted to be exposed on the surface of the death domain, which we termed the WR motif. We envisage that findings from our study will guide structural and functional studies of this important protein family.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: In silico structural model of aBaltMIP, a endogenous snake venom inhibitor from Bothrops alternatus plasma in monomeric form
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Fernandes, Carlos Alexandre Henrique; Magro, Angelo Jos√©; Fontes, Marcos Roberto de Mattos
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Phospholipases A2 (PLA2s) are important components of Bothrops snake venoms, that can induce several effects on envenomations such as myotoxicity, inhibition or induction of platelet aggregation and edema. It is known that venomous and non-venomous snakes present PLA2 inhibitory proteins (PLIs) in their blood plasma. An inhibitory protein that neutralizes the enzymatic and toxic activities of several PLA2s from Bothrops venoms was isolated from Bothrops alternatus snake plasma by affinity chromatography using the immobilized myotoxin BthTX-I on CNBr-activated Sepharose. Biochemical characterization of this inhibitory protein, denominated aBaltMIP, showed it to be a glycoprotein with Mr ofw24,000 for the monomeric subunit. CD spectra of the PLA2/inhibitor complexes are considerably different from those corresponding to the individual proteins and data deconvolution suggests that the complexes had a relative gain of helical structure elements in comparison to the individual protomers, which may indicate a more compact structure upon complexation. Theoretical and experimental structural studies performed in order to obtain insights into the structural features of aBaltMIP indicated that this molecule may potentially trimerize in solution, thus strengthening the hypothesis previously raised by other authors about snake PLIs oligomerization.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: In silico structural model of aBaltMIP, a endogenous snake venom inhibitor from Bothrops alternatus plasma in trimeric form
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Fernandes, Carlos Alexandre Henrique; Magro, Angelo Jos√©; Fontes, Marcos Roberto de Mattos
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Phospholipases A2 (PLA2s) are important components of Bothrops snake venoms, that can induce several effects on envenomations such as myotoxicity, inhibition or induction of platelet aggregation and edema. oai_dc:dc.dc:title: In silico structural model of CNF, a endogenous snake venom inhibitor from Crotalus durissus terrificus
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Fernandes, Carlos Alexandre Henrique; Fontes, Marcos Roberto de Mattos
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Several snake species possess endogenous phospholipase A2 inhibitors (sbPLIs) in their blood plasma, the primary role of which is protection against an eventual presence of toxic phospholipase A2 (PLA2) from their venom glands in the circulation. These inhibitors have an oligomeric structure of, at least, three subunits and have been categorized into three classes (Œ±, Œ≤ and Œ≥) based on their structural features. SbŒ≥PLIs have been further subdivided into two subclasses according to their hetero or homomeric nature, respectively. Despite the considerable number of sbŒ≥PLIs described, their structures and mechanisms of action are still not fully understood. In the present study, we focused on the native structure of CNF, a homomeric sbŒ≥PLI from Crotalus durissus terrificus, the South American rattlesnake. The analysis of CNF in silico structure after MD simulation confirmed that beta-sheets and loop/disordered elements formthis structure, in line with circular dichroism data. The arrangement of these secondary structure elements forms two three-finger domains, well ordered in the tertiary structure of CNF, which are typical of the sbŒ≥PLIs. Fluorescent emission intensity of tyrosines showed an inverse relationship with CNF concentration, suggesting the CNF oligomerization towards a region comprising tyrosine residues. Inspection of the solvent accessible area (SAS) of the tyrosinyl residues by the AREAIMOL software available in the CCP4 programsuite showed that six of those residues have good accessible area to solvent, in particular those in positions 16, 113, 132 and 166. These findings further confirm that a region that comprises some of those tyrosines may form the interface between the monomers in the CNF oligomerization.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: TAG protein model
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: TOMAR, JYOTI SINGH
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The DNA glycosylases participates in DNA repair mechanism, thought to be crucial component for the survival of the A. baumannii. Structure and function of this enzyme in the pathogenic bacterium A. baumannii and its closely related species are not well explored. This motivated us for the proposed in silico study, optimized modeling method is used to generate a structural scaffold on which inhibitor design is done to open a new pathway for the cure of acinetobacter. In the present work the three dimensional structure of the TAG present in A. baumannii is generated validated and compared with template 2OFK. The structure shows that most of the active site residues are conserved and overall structure of the A. baumannii and S. typhi are similar. The active site residues involved in the enzyme catalysis are well conserved.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Aada6 pseudomonas homology modelling
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Gessmann, Renate; Petratos, Kyriacos
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Antibiotic resistance of pathogenic bacteria has received immense attention over the last years as the rapid increase of multiresistant bacterial strains along with the lack of new antibiotics became a threat to global public health. Aminoglycosides are a relatively large class of antibiotics that have been employed extensively over the past decades against aerobic bacterial pathogens. They target accessible regions of polyanionic 16S rRNA on the 30S ribosomal subunit, notably the A site for aminoacyl-tRNA binding. Against aminoglycoside antibiotics, bacteria elaborated among other mechanisms of resistance enzymatic modification. Aiming at the study of the structure-function relation in this class of enzymes we focus on the protein encoded by the gene aadA6 identified in a clinical multiresistant isolate of P. aeruginosa Ps100, UniProtKB: Q9RGC2. This protein confers bacterial resistance to streptomycin and spectinomycin. A homology model of residues 3 to 262 was developed using the recently determined structure of the similar protein of salmonella enterica, pdbcode 4CS6. The substrates ATP and streptomycin were added based on the kanamycin nucleotidetransferase, pdbcode 1KNY after overlapping the beta-sheet in the N-terminal domain of both proteins and identifying the corresponding substrate binding residues. The structure was energy minimized with cns_solve.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: FUR dimer Escherichia coli
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Crouzy, Serge
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: ABSTRACT The FUR protein (Ferric Uptake Regulator) is an iron-dependent global transcriptional regulator. Specific to bacteria, FUR is an attractive antibacterial target since virulence is correlated to iron bioavailability. No complete experimental structure of FUR from Escherichia coli is available to date. Here, a model of EcFUR dimer from residue 2 to 134 is built by homology from FUR vibrio cholerae (more than 80% similar residues). Model is refined by energy minimization with the CHARMM molecular mechanics force field in implicit solvent. Model is validated in two ways : i) both monomers superimpose very well with the known crystal structure of the N-terminal domain (2FU4) ii) Docking of inhibitor peptides to the EcFUR model dimer agree with in vitro assays. The model includes 4 Fe2+ and 2 Zn2+ metal ions in their putative respective binding sites.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: In silico structural model of OB-fold domains 1 and 2 from Replication Protein A1 from Trypanosoma cruzi
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Fernandes, Carlos Alexandre Henrique; Matioli, Fabio Filippi; Fontes, Marcos Roberto de Mattos; Pavani, Raphael de Souza; Elias, Maria Carolina
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Replication Protein A (RPA) is the major single-stranded binding protein from eukaryotes. RPA is a conserved heterotrimeric complex composed by subunits RPA-1, RPA-2 and RPA-3 (or RPA70, RPA32 and RPA14 respectively). One of the major structural features of RPA is the presence of the oligonucleotide/oligosaccharide binding (OB) domains within the subunits. Here, we created the in silico model of OB-fold domains 1 and 2 of RPA1 from Trypanosoma cruzi in order to evaluate the DNA binding mode.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Structure of human Orai1 based on homology with dOrai
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Ettrich, Rudiger H.; Zayats, Vasilina
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The STIM/Orai channel complex provides a major route for physiological Ca2+ signaling in immune cells, as well as in skin, muscle and other tissues . Understanding this Ca2+ entry pathway has important patho-physiological implications including autoimmunity, atherosclerosis and cancer progression. Structural insight into the Orai channel from Drosophila melanogaster recently depicts a hexameric assembly of Orai subunits arranged around a central ion pore . Six transmembrane helices compose the funnel structured pore that extends into the cytosol. The pore-forming transmembrane helix determines both gating and ion permeation. To provide insight into Ca2+ sensing and permeation, we took advantage of the high sequence identity of the crystallized Drosophila melanogaster Orai channel of 63% to human Orai1 to obtain a 3D homology model of human Orai1 including the loops missing in the Drosophila crystal structure. To test the principal stability of the refined and deposited human Orai1 model, the model was embedded in a POPC lipid bilayer and 100ns long molecular dynamics simulations were performed. The model has one Ca2+ ion placed into the selectivity filter, near E106 to stabilize its geometry during equilibration. Throughout the full time of the molecular dynamics simulation, the hexameric channel maintained its secondary and tertiary structure and also kept structural symmetry of all six subunits. The model was then used in the cited work to investigate the pore entrance and its ability to form a calcium accumulating region, i.e. CAR.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: In silico structural model of OB-fold domain from Replication Protein A2 from Trypanosoma cruzi
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Fernandes, Carlos Alexandre Henrique; Matioli, Fabio Filippi; Fontes, Marcos Roberto de Mattos; Pavani, Raphael de Souza; Elias, Maria Carolina
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Replication Protein A (RPA) is the major single-stranded binding protein from eukaryotes. RPA is a conserved heterotrimeric complex composed by subunits RPA-1, RPA-2 and RPA-3 (or RPA70, RPA32 and RPA14 respectively). One of the major structural features of RPA is the presence of the oligonucleotide/oligosaccharide binding (OB) domains within the subunits. Here, we created the in silico model of OB-fold domain of RPA2 from Trypanosoma cruzi in order to evaluate the DNA binding mode. Here we show that TcRPA-2 has a insertion containig glycines and alanines in a loop close to DNA binding channel. In fact, this region during molecular dynamics (MD) simulations presented a high root mean square fluctuation (r.m.s.f.) of the main chain, adopting multiple positions during of 50 ns of MD simulation, often even occluding DNA binding channel. This data suggest that DNA binding site on TcRPA-2 is more structurally unstable than upper eukaryotes, which can promote changes on the DNA binding affinity of TcRPA-2.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Full Length 3D Monomer Structure of Human Tumor Suppressor Protein p53 Using Homology Based Approach Combined with a Refinement process
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Raghavan, Vaijayanthi; Agrahari, Maulishree; Dhankale, Dhananjaya Kalegowda
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: p53 is a very important Tumor Suppressor Protein that plays key roles in many cellular mechanisms thus preventing the development of cancers in humans. Its gene, TP53 is positioned on chromosome 17p13 and encodes a 53 kilodalton nucleophosphoprotein which is a transcription factor with a central role in cell cycle regulation. However, mutations in this protein lead to various types of human cancers and it is estimated that more than 50% of human cancers are due to missense mutations found in p53 [1]. Till date individual domain structures determined by various experimental methods are available but complete 3D structure is yet to be resolved. One of the major challenges faced in determining the complete structure of human p53 is the stability issue of wild type p53 as this protein is only marginally stable at physiological conditions making it difficult to handle this protein in the laboratory. As a consequence, most of the p53 research activities has been based on the super stable quadruple structure of p53 known as T-p53C, which has been engineered by inducing single point mutations in four different positions (M133L/V203A/N239Y/N268D) of wild type human p53. It is claimed by the authors that this designed protein has the same DNA binding and other properties as the wild type p53 but with enhanced stability [Nikolova P. V., et al., 1998]. Thus there has been a need to have access to full length structure of p53 and this has been the driving force to adopt computational approaches to model wildtype p53. Homology based model building method combined with iterative process were used to build the full length Human p53 protein 3D structure. Modeler integrated with the licensed version of Discovery studio version 3.5 was used to generate an initial model with nine different PDB templates and an iterative approach was further used to build a refined model. Validation reports were generated for the final model and it was found to be an acceptable quality model of p53. Energy minimization using Gromacs tool was performed on the final model generating a final energy minimized full length model of human p53.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Model of G-alpha-i3 bound to the GIV GBA-motif
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: DiGiacomo, Vincent; Garcia-Marcos, Mikel
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description:
The activation of heterotrimeric G proteins is typically achieved by guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF) proteins that facilitate the exchange of GDP for GTP on G-alpha subunits. While this exchange activity is typically performed by G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs), cytosolic non-receptor type GEFs have been more recently described as G-alpha activators. A subset of the described non-receptor GEFs contain a Galpha-Binding and Activating (GBA) motif. This short, evolutionarily conserved motif is known to confer nucleotide exchange activity to non-receptor GEFs such as GIV/Girdin, but there is limited structural information available for the interaction.
Combining homology modeling with protein-protein docking and ab initio structure prediction, we constructed a model of the G-alpha-i3 interface with GIV (residues 1678-1696), mapping the binding of the GBA motif to a cleft formed by the alpha3 helix and the Switch II region of G-alpha. This model was validated using a host of biochemical assays in addition to NMR spectroscopy, and has implications for the field of G-protein biology, nucleotide exchange, and therapeutic development.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Human and mouse Potassium Channels
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Johner, Niklaus
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The Human Brain Project aims at better understanding the function of the mouse and human brains. Potassium channels are central to the function of the brain as they play a crucial role in the generation and control of action potentials. In this framework we have created homology models of the human and mouse potassium channels which provide a structural framework for the study of their function. These models allow us to study the interplay between the structure and the function of potassium channels. We are notably trying to understand what structural features determine important functional rates such as the C-type inactivation rate, and use this understanding to predict these kinetic rates for channels for which experimental data is not available.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Rearrangement of the extracellular domain/extracellular loop 1 interface is critical for thyrotropin receptor activation
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Schaarschmidt, Joerg; Nagel, Marcus B. M.; Huth, Sandra; J√§schke, Holger; Moretti, Rocco; Hintze, Vera; von Bergen, Martin; Kalkhof, Stefan; Meiler, Jens; Paschke, Ralf
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The thyroid stimulating hormone receptor (TSHR) is a G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR) with a characteristic large extracellular domain (ECD). TSHR activation is initiated by binding of the hormone ligand TSH to the ECD. How the extracellular binding event triggers the conformational changes in the transmembrane domain (TMD) necessary for intracellular G protein activation is poorly understood. To gain insight in this process, the knowledge on the relative positioning of ECD and TMD and the conformation of the linker region at the interface of ECD and TMD are of particular importance. In order toTo generate a structural model for the TSHR we applied an integrated structural biology approach combining computational techniques with experimental data. Chemical crosslinking followed by mass spectrometry (XL-MS) yielded 17 unique distance restraints within the ECD of the TSHR, its ligand TSH and the hormone/receptor complex. These structural restraints generally confirm the expected binding mode of TSH to the ECD as well as the general fold of the domains and were used to guide homology modelling of the ECD. Functional characterization of TSHR mutants confirms the previously suggested close proximity of S281 and I486 within the TSHR. Rigidifying this contact permanently with a disulfide bridge disrupts ligand-induced receptor activation and indicates that rearrangement of the ECD/extra-cellular loop (ECL) 1 interface is a critical step in receptor activation. The experimentally verified contact of S281 (ECD) and I486 (TMD) was subsequently utilized in docking homology models of the ECD and the TMD to create a full-length model of a GPHR.

oai_dc:dc.dc:description: A three-step purification of a unique lipase with halo-, solvent-, detergent- and themo-tolerance from Staphylococcus arlettae JPBW-1gave rise a 27-fold purification with a specific activity of 32.5 U/mg. The molecular weight of the purified lipase was estimated to be 45 kDa using SDS‚ÄìPAGE, whose amino acid sequence was characterized using MALDI-TOF-MS analysis. The sequence obtained from MALDI-TOF-MS showed significant similarity with the capsular polysaccharide biosynthesis protein (CapD) of Staphylococcus auerus. Using biochemical and bioinformatics methods we report a unique lipase that exhibits unique properties and thus a potential candidate for industrial applications.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Xenorhabdus nematophila RelE antitoxin
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Gautam, Lalit Kumar; Yennamalli, Ragothaman M; Rathore, Jitendra Singh
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Bacterial chromosomal ‚Äòtoxin-antitoxin systems‚Äô (TA systems) are involved in various cell functions such as stress response, promoting cell cycle arrest and bringing about the onset of programmed cell death. Unlike RelBE TA module of Escherichia coli, genome of Xenorhabdus nematophila has two separate TA modules for RelB and RelE. Here RelE being the toxin bears its own antitoxin and RelB antitoxin bears its separate toxin counterpart. More interestingly these modules are located distantly in genome. In this study, Xn-relE toxin from X. nematophila is reported for the first time and our earlier report has shown the toxic effect of Xn-relE toxin by endogenous killing (Rathore and Gautam, 2014). Since no crystallographic structure for this toxin is available till date, we report a homology model for X. nematophila Xn-relE toxin and its antitoxin Xn-relEAT. The model was analyzed using the I-TASSER server for structure prediction and defining gene ontology. The model was validated by using VERIFY-3D. The structure shares homology with previously reported Type II TA complexes. The predicted model sheds light on the structure-function studies of Xn-relE toxin, whose applicability in the area of agricultural sciences is pronounced.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: PfPARE
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Istvan, Eva S; Goldberg, Daniel E
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: We investigated the reported order-of-magnitude variance in potency of the aspartic protease inhibitor pepstatin against asexual Plasmodium falciparum. From a more potent preparation, we isolated the fraction that had strong anti-parasitic activity and identified the active component as butyl ester-modified pepstatin. We synthesized a number of derivatives and characterized an analog (pepstatin hexyl ester) with low nanomolar activity. Compared to the ester derivatives, charged pepstatin is poorly taken up by parasites. Pepstatin ester-resistant parasites were readily obtained. Full-genome sequencing revealed SNPs in a putative esterase, PF3D7_0709700. Resistance-conferring mutations were in the C-terminal helix or close to the active site; others had nonsense mutations resulting in enzyme truncation. Knock-in of esterase-inactivating mutations did not affect parasite growth and made pepstatin esters inert. Parasites with esterase mutations were also resistant to a compound from the Medicines for Malaria Venture (MMV) collection of antimalarials, MMV011438. Recombinant esterase hydrolyzed pepstatin esters and de-esterified MMV011438. We conclude that 1) pepstatin is a potent, but poorly bioavailable anti-malarial; 2) PF3D7_0709700 is an active esterase with moderate substrate specificity that is capable of activating prodrugs; 3) Mutations in this esterase constitute a new mechanism of antimalarial resistance.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Xn-RelT toxin from X. nematophila in complex with Xn-RelAT antitoxin.
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Gautam, Lalit Kumar; Rathore, Jitendra Singh
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Toxin‚Äìantitoxin (TA) complexes play role in stress responses and programmed cell death in bacteria. The RelB-RelE toxin antitoxin system is well studied in Escherichia coli. In this study, we used combined in silico and in vivo approaches to study a novel Xn-RelT toxin from Xenorhabdus nematophila bearing its own antitoxin Xn-RelAT, a RelB homologue of E. coli. The structure for this toxin- antitoxin pair is yet unknown. We generated homology based models of X. nematophila RelT toxin and antitoxin. Deduced models were further analysed for protein-nucleic acid, protein-protein interactions and functional characterization based on gene ontology. Detrimental effect of recombinant Xn-RelT on host E. coli was determined through endogenous toxicity assay.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Structural determination of hexose transporter Plasmodium falciparum (PfHT) by homology modeling
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Fonseca, Amanda Luisa da; Nunes, Renata Rachide; Comar Jr, Moacyr; Alves, Ricardo Jos√©; Varotti, Fernando de Pilla; Taranto, Alex Gutterres
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Malaria is the most prevalent parasitic disease in the world. Currently, an effective vaccine for malaria does not exist, and chemotherapy must be used to treat the disease. Because of increasing resistance to current antimalarial drugs, new treatments must be developed. Among the many potential molecular targets, the hexose transporter of Plasmodium falciparum (PfHT) is particularly promising because it plays a vital role in glucose transport for the parasite. Thus, this study aims to determine the three-dimensional structure of PfHT and to describe the intermolecular interactions between active glycoside derivatives and PfHT. Such information should aid in the development of new antimalarial drugs. The receptor PfHT was constructed from primary sequences deposited in the SWISS MODEL database. Next, molecular docking simulations between O-(undec-10-en)-l-D-glucose and the constructed active site models were performed using Autodock Vina. The glycoside derivative-PfHT complexes were then refined using the hybrid QM/MM (PM3/ff03) method within the AMBER package. The models were then evaluated using Ramachandran plots, which indicated that 93.2% of the residues in the refined PfHT models (P5) were present in favorable regions. Furthermore, graphical plots using ANOLEA showed that the potential energies of interaction for atoms unbonded to P5 were negative. Finally, the O-(undec-10-en)-l-D-glucose-PfHT complex was evaluated using 20-ns Molecular Dynamics simulations with an ff03 force field. Docking and QM/MM studies revealed the amino acids essential for molecular recognition of and activity on glycosides. Inhibition of glucose transporters may prevent the development and metabolism of P. falciparum, so a description of the receptor‚Äôs structure is a critical step towards rational drug design.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: IBDV VP5
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Ganguly, Bhaskar
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Infectious Bursal Disease (IBD) is an acute, highly contagious and immunosuppressive disease of young chicken. The causative virus (IBDV) is a bi-segmented, double-stranded RNA virus. The virus encodes five major proteins, viral protein (VP) 1‚Äì5. VPs 1‚Äì3 have been characterized crystallographically. Albeit a rise in the number of studies reporting successful heterologous expression of VP5 in recent times, challenging the notion that rapid death of host cells overexpressing VP5 disallows obtaining sufficiently pure preparations of the protein for crystallographic studies, the structure of VP5 remains unknown and its function controversial. Our study describes the first 3D model of IBD VP5 obtained through an elaborate computational workflow. Based on the results of the study, IBD VP5 can be predicted to be a structural analog of the leucine-rich repeat (LRR) family of proteins. Functional implications arising from structural similarity of VP5 with host Toll-like receptor (Tlr) 3 also satisfy the previously reported opposing roles of the protein in first abolishing and later inducing host-cell apoptosis.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Quantitative FRET studies and integrative modeling unravel the structure and dynamics of biomolecular systems
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Dimura, Mykola; Peulen, Thomas Otavio; Hanke, Christian Alexander; Prakash, Aiswaria; Gohlke, Holger; Seidel, Claus A.M.
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: F√∂rster Resonance Energy Transfer (FRET) combined with single- molecule spectroscopy probes macromolecular structure and dynamics and identifies coexisting conformational states. We review recent methodological developments in integrative structural modeling by satisfying spatial restraints on networks of FRET pairs (hybrid-FRET). We discuss procedures to incorporate prior structural knowledge and to obtain optimal distance networks. Finally, a workflow for hybrid-FRET is presented that automates integrative structural modeling and experiment planning to put hybrid-FRET on rails. To test this workflow, we simulate realistic single-molecule experiments and resolve three protein conformers, exchanging at 30 Œºs and 10 ms, with accuracies of 1 - 3 √Ö RMSD versus the target structure. Incorporation of data from other spectroscopies and imaging is also discussed.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Single amino acid substitutions in the selectivity filter render NbXIP1;1Œ± aquaporin water permeable - Wild Type
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Ampah-Korsah, Henry; Sonntag, Yonathan; Engfors, Angelica; Kirscht, Andreas; Kjellbom, Per; Johanson, Urban
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Aquaporins (AQPs) are integral membrane proteins that facilitate transport of water and/or other small neutral solutes across membranes in all forms of life. The X Intrinsic Proteins (XIPs) are the most recently recognized and the least characterized aquaporin subfamily in higher plants. XIP1s have been shown to be impermeable to water but permeable to boric acid, glycerol, hydrogen peroxide and urea. However, uncertainty of the determinants for selectivity and lack of an activity that is easy to quantify in spheroplasts, have hindered functional investigations. In an effort to resolve these issues, we set out to introduce water permeability in Nicotiana benthamiana NbXIP1;1Œ± (NbXIP1;1Œ±), by exchanging predicted alternative aromatic/arginine (ar/R) selectivity filters of NbXIP1;1Œ± for the water permeable ar/R selectivity filter of AtTIP2;1.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Models of transcription factor LasR
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Bagchi, Angshuman; Chowdhury, Nilkanta
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Pseudomonas aeruginosa, an opportunistic human pathogen can attack human patients suffering from different diseases like AIDS, cancer, cystic Ô¨Åbrosis, etc. The organism codes for a virulent factor called Hydrogen Cyanide (HCN). HCN is encoded by an operon called hcnABC operon. The expressions of the hcnABC operon are carried out by binding of LasR protein with the corresponding promoter DNA region of the hcnABC operon. Till date no studies have been performed to analyze the molecular details of the binding interactions of LasR with the promoter DNA. This is the first report which elucidates the molecular mechanism of the binding interactions of LasR with the promoter DNA.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: In silico structural model of OB-fold domains 3 from Replication Protein A1 from Trypanosoma cruzi
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Fernandes, Carlos Alexandre Henrique; Matioli, Fabio Filippi; Fontes, Marcos Roberto de Mattos; Pavani, Raphael de Souza; Elias, Maria Carolina
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Replication Protein A (RPA) is the major single-stranded binding protein from eukaryotes. RPA is a conserved heterotrimeric complex composed by subunits RPA-1, RPA-2 and RPA-3 (or RPA70, RPA32 and RPA14 respectively). One of the major structural features of RPA is the presence of the oligonucleotide/oligosaccharide binding (OB) domains within the subunits. Here, we created the in silico model of OB-fold domains 3 of RPA1 from Trypanosoma cruzi in order to evaluate the DNA binding mode. We show that DNA could not bind on OBF3 of RPA1 from T.cruzi in contrast to RPA1 from upper eukaryotes that bind DNA in the three OB-fold domains.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Homology model of ANR from Pseudomonas aeruginosa
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Bagchi, Angshuman; Chowdhury, Nilkanta
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Pseudomonas aeruginosa is a deadly opportunistic human pathogen. The organism codes for different virulence factors and among them is HCN synthesized by HCN synthase enzyme. the enzyme is encoded by the hcnABC operon. It is to be noted that the expression of the genes of the hcnABC operon are regulated by LasR, ANR and RhlR proteins. ANR protein belongs to the FNR family. It works in anaerobic condition. It binds to the promoter DNA as a dimer. Till date the residue level binding interactions of ANR with the promoter DNA have not yet been established. Therefore, we tried to identify the binding interactions of ANR protein with the promoter DNA from a structural bioinformatics approach.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Master regulator, DnrI of Streptomyces peucetius
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Francis, Prija; Sekar, Vaishnavi; Betharasu, Raguram
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The master regulator, DnrI of Streptomyces peucetius is a member of the family of transcriptional activator, Streptomyces antibiotic regulatory proteins (SARP), which controls the biosynthesis of antitumor anthracycline, daunorubicin (DNR) and doxorubicin (DXR). DnrI is a winged helix turn helix DNA binding protein with two domains: DNA binding domain (DBD) and Bacterial Transcription Activator Domain (BTAD). The three dimensional structure of transcriptional regulatory protein, DnrI was modeled with the template EmbR (2FEZ), a regulatory protein with ATPase activity of Mycobacterium tuberculosis. DnrI is categorized under Class All alpha proteins, Fold alpha-alpha superhelix, superfamily TPR-like. It has two clans HTH (CL0123) and Tetroco peptide repeat (CL0020) which have family Trans_reg_C (PF00486) and Bacterial transcriptional Activator Domain (PF03704).Till date no structure for daunorubicin regulatory protein has been elucidated experimentally.

oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Large Scale determination of previously unsolved protein structures using evolutionary information
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Ovchinnikov, Sergey; Baker, David
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The prediction of the structures of proteins without detectable sequence similarity to any protein of known structure remains an outstanding scientific challenge. Here we describe de novo blind structure predictions of unprecedented accuracy for two proteins in large families made in the recent CASP11 blind test of protein structure prediction methods by incorporating residue-residue co-evolution information in the Rosetta structure prediction program. We then use the method to generate structure models for 58 of the 121 large protein families in prokaryotes for which three dimensional structures are not available. These models, which are posted online for public access, provide structural information for the over 400,000 proteins belonging to the 58 families and suggest hypotheses about mechanism for the subset for which the function is known, and hypotheses about function for the remainder.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: A structural preview of aquaporin 8 via homology modeling of seven vertebrate isoforms - HsAQP8
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Kirscht, Andreas; Sonntag, Yonathan; Kjellbom, Per; Johanson, Urban
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Background Aquaporins (AQPs) facilitate the passage of small neutral polar molecules across membranes of the cell. In animals there are four distinct AQP subfamilies, whereof AQP8 homologues constitute one of the smallest subfamilies with just one member in man. AQP8 conducts water, ammonia, urea, glycerol and H2O2 through various membranes of animal cells. This passive channel has been connected to a number of effects, such as volume change of mitochondria, ammonia neurotoxicity, and mitochondrial dysfunction related to oxidative stress. Currently there is no experimentally determined structure of an AQP8, hence the structural understanding of this subfamily is limited. oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Arsenate Reductase (ArsC) of Deinococcus indicus DR1
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Chauhan, Deepika; Srivastava, Pulkit Anupam; Agnihotri, Vidushi; Yennamalli, Ragothaman M; Priyadarshini, Richa
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Tolerance to Arsenic, either as the pentavalent [As(V)] form or the trivalent form [As(III)], by bacteria has been well studied in prokaryotes and the mechanism of action is well defined. However, in the rod-shaped highly arsenic tolerant Deinococcus indicus the key enzyme, arsenate reductase (ArsC) has not been well studied. While it shares homology with the well-studied ArsC of E.coli, we report that the mechanism of action of As(V) is different and most likely due to a result of convergent evolution. Here, we report that D.indicus is most likely able to detoxify As(V) using a mix of positively- and negatively-charged residues in its active site, unlike the residues of E.coli.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Intracellular cavity of sensor domain controls allosteric gating of TRPA1 channel
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Barvik, Ivan; Zima, Vlastimil
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Transient receptor potential ankyrin 1 (TRPA1) is a temperature-sensitive ion channel activated by various pungent and irritant compounds that can produce pain in humans. Its activation involves an allosteric mechanism whereby electrophilic agonists evoke interactions within cytosolic domains and open the channel pore throughan integrated nexus formed by intracellular membrane proximal regions that are densely packed beneath the lower segment of the S1-S4 sensor domain. Studies indicate that this part of the channel may contain residues that form a water-accessible cavity that undergoes changes in solvation during channel gating. Here we identified conserved polar residues facing the putative lower crevice of the sensor domain that were crucial determinants of the electrophilic, voltage and calcium sensitivity of the TRPA1 channel. This part of the sensor may also comprise a domain capable of binding membrane phosphoinositides through which the channel‚Äôs gating is regulated in a state-dependent manner.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: full-length wild-type p53 tetramer with DNA
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Demir, Ozlem; Offutt, Tavina L.; Ieong, Pek U; Amaro, Rommie E.
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: To explore p53 structural dynamics, we used the available crystal structures of p53 parts and molecular modeling and developed an atomistic integrative model of the full-length p53 tetramer bound to the DNA sequence of a p21 response element. Here we have deposited the DNA-bound full-length p53 tetramer model after molecular dynamics simulations in explicit solvent.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Mycoplasma pneumoniae RNA polymerase
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Graziadei, Andrea; O Reilly, Francis; Xue, Liang; Mahamid, Julia; Rappsilber, Juri
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Structural biology performed inside cells can capture molecular machines in action within their native context. Here we developed an integrative in-cell structural approach using the genome-reduced human pathogen Mycoplasma pneumoniae. We combined whole-cell crosslinking mass spectrometry, cellular cryo-electron tomography, and integrative modeling to determine an in-cell architecture of a transcribing and translating expressome at sub-nanometer resolution. The expressome comprises RNA polymerase (RNAP), the ribosome, and the transcription elongation factors NusG and NusA. We pinpointed NusA at the interface between a NusG-bound elongating RNAP and the ribosome, and propose it could mediate transcription-translation coupling. Translation inhibition dissociated the expressome, whereas transcription inhibition stalled and rearranged it. Thus, the active expressome architecture requires both translation and transcription elongation within the cell.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: In silico structure of OB-fold domains 1 and 2 of RPA1 from Trypanosoma cruzi docked a single stranded telomeric DNA
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Fernandes, Carlos Alexandre Henrique; Matiolli, Fabio Filippi; Pavani, Raphael Souza; Fontes, Marcos Roberto de Mattos; Elias, Maria Carolina Quartiam
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Replication Protein A (RPA) is the major single-stranded binding protein from eukaryotes. RPA is a conserved heterotrimeric complex composed by subunits RPA-1, RPA-2 and RPA-3 (or RPA70, RPA32 and RPA14, respectively). One of the major structural features of RPA is the presence of the oligonucleotide/oligosaccharide binding (OB) domains within the subunits. Here, we performed docking experiments and molecular dynamics simulations of TcRPA-1-OBF12 in silico model (previously reported at doi: 10.5452/ma-azgkp) with asingle stranded telomeric DNA (TTAGGGTTAG) in order to evaluate protein/DNA interactions.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Structural characterization of an Arf dimer interface: molecular mechanism of Arf-dependent membrane scission
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Nunes-Alves, Ariane; Wade, Rebecca C.; Hanke, Anton
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description:
The aim of the work was to model the homodimer of Arf1. Interaction interfaces were predicted using the web servers PINTS and meta-PPISP. The dimer was predicted by rigid-body docking using ClusPro. The model obtained agrees with experimental data from hydrogen exchange mass spectrometry.
Please read the note in the Procedure section regarding the inaccuracies in the GTP structure.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Xenorhabdus nematophila RelE toxin
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Gautam, Lalit Kumar; Yennamalli, Ragothaman M; Rathore, Jitendra Singh
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Bacterial chromosomal ‚Äòtoxin-antitoxin systems‚Äô (TA systems) are involved in various cell functions such as stress response, promoting cell cycle arrest and bringing about the onset of programmed cell death. Unlike RelBE TA module of Escherichia coli, genome of Xenorhabdus nematophila has two separate TA modules for RelB and RelE. Here RelE being the toxin bears its own antitoxin and RelB antitoxin bears its separate toxin counterpart. More interestingly these modules are located distantly in genome. In this study, Xn-relE toxin from X. nematophila is reported for the first time and our earlier report has shown the toxic effect of Xn-relE toxin by endogenous killing (Rathore and Gautam, 2014). Since no crystallographic structure for this toxin is available till date, we report a homology model for X. nematophila Xn-relE toxin and its antitoxin Xn-relEAT. The model was analyzed using the I-TASSER server for structure prediction and defining gene ontology. The model was validated by using VERIFY-3D. The structure shares homology with previously reported Type II TA complexes. The predicted model sheds light on the structure-function studies of Xn-relE toxin, whose applicability in the area of agricultural sciences is pronounced.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Mouse Eugenol Odorant Receptor
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Spreafico, Morena; Schwede, Torsten
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Molecular interactions of odorants with their olfactory receptors (ORs) are of central importance for the ability of the mammalian olfactory system to detect and discriminate a vast variety of odors with a limited set of receptors. How a particular OR binds and distinguishes different odorant molecules remains largely unknown on a structural basis. Here we investigated this question for the mouse eugenol receptor (mOR-EG). By screening a large odorant library, we discovered a wide range of chemical structures activating the receptor in heterologous mammalian cells. Potent agonists comprise (i) benzene, (ii) cyclohexane, or (iii) polycyclic structures substituted with alcohol, aldehyde, keto, ether, or esterified carboxylic groups. To detect those amino acids within the receptor that are in contact with a particular bound odorant molecule, we investigated how distinct mOR-EG point mutants were activated by the different odorant agonists found for the wild-type receptor. We identified 11 amino acids as a part of the receptor‚Äôs ligand binding pocket. Molecular modeling predicted 10 of these residues in transmembrane helices TM3‚àíTM6 and one in the extracellular loop between TM2 and TM3. These amino acids participate in odorant binding with variable importance depending on the type of odorant, revealing functional ‚Äúfingerprints‚Äù of ligand‚àíreceptor interactions.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: CYP21A2Bruque2016
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Bruque, Carlos David; Dain, Liliana; Nadra, Alejandro Daniel
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: A model of the human CYP21A2 protein based on the structure of the bovine CYP21A2 (PDB ID: 3QZ1) was generated using MODELLER version 9.11 including heme cofactor explicitly. Amino acid sequence was taken from UniProt (NP_000491.4) while alignments were performed with MEGA 4 software. A significant improvement of the model was obtained by manually displacing L129 in the automatic alignment and iterative loop refinement. The use of multiple templates of other proteins of the CYP family did not improve the model. Model‚Äôs quality was assessed by DOPE, QMEAN Z-scores and Ramachandran plots.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: 11-deoxy-PGE1 docked Human Prostanoid E2 Receptor Subtype 4 (hEP4)
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Holt, Melissa Christine; Stein, Adam J.
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The EP4 prostanoid receptor is one of four GPCRs that mediate the diverse actions of prostaglandin E2 (PGE2). Novel selective EP4 receptor agonists would assist to further elucidate receptor sub-type function and promote development of therapeutics for bone healing, heart failure, and other receptor associated conditions. Homology models were generated by threading for rat and human EP4 receptors using the RaptorX server. These models were fit to an implicit membrane using the PPM server and OPM database with refinement of intra and extracellular loops by Prime (Schr√∂dinger). To understand the interaction between the receptors and known agonists, induced-fit docking experiments were performed using Glide (Schr√∂dinger) and Prime, with both endogenous agonists and receptor sub-type selective, small-molecule agonists.

oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: TOMAR, JYOTI SINGH
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Demand of present day scenario for drug resistivity is the discovery of novel antibacterial targets to fight with multidrug-resistant infection causing pathogens. Hpa2, a member of GNAT superfamily of HATs. In twilight zone, modelling of protein structure having good quality become a difficult task. To overcome these problems, an modified protocol was developed for modelling of Hpa2 monomer and protein-protein docking. Validation for structural parameters and model stability analysis confirmed that these models are of good quality. Determination of the interfacial residues and contribution of energy terms indicate clear correlations between the experimental and theoretical interface properties of dimer, corroborating to the used regime.

Translation inhibition dissociated the expressome, whereas transcription inhibition stalled and rearranged it. Thus, the active expressome architecture requires both translation and transcription elongation within the cell.

oai_dc:dc.dc:description:
Oxytocin-Gly-Lys-Arg: A Novel Cardiomyogenic Peptide
BACKGROUND: Oxytocin (OT), synthesized in the heart, has the ability to heal injured hearts and to promote cardiomyogenesis from stem cells. Recently, we reported that the OT-GKR molecule, a processing intermediate of OT, potently increased the spontaneous formation of cardiomyocytes (CM) in embryonic stem D3 cells and augmented glucose uptake in newborn rat CM above the level stimulated by OT. In the present experiments, we investigated whether OT-GKR exists in fetal and newborn rodent hearts, interacts with the OT receptors (OTR) and primes the generation of contracting cells expressing CM markers in P19 cells, a model for the study of early heart differentiation.
METHODOLOGY/PRINCIPAL FINDINGS: High performance liquid chromatography of newborn rat heart extracts indicated that OT-GKR was a dominant form of OT. Immunocytochemistry of mouse embryos (embryonic day 15) showed cardiac OT-GKR accumulation and OTR expression. Computerized molecular modeling revealed OT-GKR docking to active OTR sites and to V1a receptor of vasopressin. In embryonic P19 cells, OT-GKR induced contracting cell colonies and ventricular CM markers more potently than OT, an effect being suppressed by OT antagonists and OTR-specific small interfering (si) RNA. The V1a receptor antagonist and specific si-RNA also significantly reduced OT-GKR-stimulated P19 contracting cells. In comparison to OT, OT-GKR induced in P19 cells less Œ±-actinin, myogenin and MyoD mRNA, skeletal muscle markers.
CONCLUSIONS/SIGNIFICANCE: These results raise the possibility that C-terminally extended OT molecules stimulate CM differentiation and contribute to heart growth during fetal life.

oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Heat-shock proteins of 70 kDa (Hsp70s) are vital in nearly all forms of life, notably important for protein folding. Hsp70s use ATP binding and hydrolysis at a nucleotide-binding domain (NBD) to control the binding and release of polypeptide substrates at a substrate-binding domain (SBD); however, the mechanistic basis for this allosteric action has been elusive. In this paper, we tested biochemical properties of selected domain-interface mutants in Hsp70 DnaK-ATP and, using these observations, developed and experimentally quantified a theoretical model for allosteric equilibria among Hsp70 conformational states. A restraining state, Hsp70-ATPR, restricts ATP hydrolysis and binds peptides poorly; whereas a stimulating state, Hsp70-ATPS, hydrolyzes ATP rapidly and has high intrinsic substrate affinity but rapid binding kinetics. A companion paper provided the confirming structure of DnaK-ATPR; conformational constraints and mutant properties facilitated an atomic model for DnaK-ATPS, which is the subject of this model deposition. Biochemical tests of novel interfacial contacts in DnaK-ATPS corroborate both the model and the theory.

oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Catecholamine neurotransmitter levels in the synapses of the brain shape human disposition ‚Äî cognitive flexibility, aggression, depression, reward seeking‚Ä¶ ‚Äî and manipulating these levels is a major objective of the pharmaceutical industry. Certain transmitters are extensively sulfonated ‚Äî an inactivating modification catalyzed by human sulfotransferase 1A3 (SULT1A3). To our knowledge, sulfonation as therapeutic means of regulating transmitter activity has not been explored. Here we describe the discovery of a SULT1A3 allosteric site that can be used to inhibit the enzyme. The structure of the new site is determined using spin-label-triangulation NMR. The site forms a cleft at the edge of a conserved ~30-residue active-site cap that must open and close during the catalytic cycle. Allosteres anchor into the site via œÄ stacking interactions with two residues that sandwich the planar core of the allostere, and inhibit the enzyme through cap-stabilizing interactions with substituents attached to the core. The cap free energy was calculated ab initio as a function of the substituents, and the calculations were used to designand synthesizea series of inhibitors intended to progressively stabilize the cap and slow turnover. The inhibitors bound tightly (34 nM ‚Äì 7.4 ŒºM) and exhibited progressive inhibition (0 ‚Äì 80%). The cap stabilizing effects of the inhibitors were experimentally determined and agreed remarkably well with the theoretical predictions. These studies establish a reliable heuristic for the design of SULT1A3 allosteric inhibitors and demonstrate that the free-energy changes of a small, dynamic loop that is critical for SULT substrate selection and turnover can be calculatedaccurately.

XIP1s have been shown to be impermeable to water but permeable to boric acid, glycerol, hydrogen peroxide and urea. oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Structural insight on ATP hydrolysis in RecA/ssDNA nucleofilament
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Pr√©vost, Chantal; Boyer, Benjamin; Danilowicz, Claudia; Prentiss, Mara
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: 3D macromolecular model
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Homologous recombination (HR) is a fundamental process that allows the faithful repair of DNA double strand breaks through the exchange of DNA strands between homologous regions of the genome. In bacteria, the exchange takes place within nucleofilaments of the RecA protein formed on a DNA strand from the damaged region. ATP is hydrolyzed in large quantity during the HR process, yet how exactly hydrolysis influences the DNA strand exchange reaction at the structural level remains to be elucidated. This project examines the putative implication of a single ATP hydrolysis event on the structure, position, and interactions of up to three DNA strands within the RecA nucleofilament. The present structure represents two turns of RecA nucleofilament (12 RecA monomers) bound to a single-stranded DNA and presenting a central ADP-bound interface within a filament otherwise in the active ATP-bound form.
